Satawu spokesperson Zanele Sabela says the union is disappointed SAA CEO Vuyani Jarana has resigned. JOHANNESBURG - The South African Transport and Allied Workers Union says it is disappointed at South African Airways CEO Vuyani Jarana's resignation. Jarana cited a lack of support for the ailing airline's turnaround strategy and uncertainty about funding as reasons for his resignation. READ: SAA CEO Vuyani Jarana resigns Satawu spokesperson Zanele Sabela described Jarana as a consultative person who laid out great plans for taking the airline forward. "There were a few measures that were pointing to things going in a certain direction as he had centralised procurement to make sure costs were controlled,” Sabela said. "Our representative at SAA had confidence in him.